### TITLE ###
ArgsBlockTypedUseFlagsMismatch
### DESCRIPTION ###
An args-block decl is now a typed binding: passing it to a typed
slot of an incompatible type fires RAD30001.
### INPUT ###
args:
    name str

fn greet(label: int):
    print(label)

greet(name)
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  print @ 5:5 -> dynamic
  label @ 5:11 -> int
  greet @ 7:1 -> fn(int) -> void
  name @ 7:7 -> str

# Symbol types
  greet (fn): fn(int) -> void
  label (param): int
  name (arg): str

# Diagnostics
  [hint] RAD30001 @ 7:7 - Argument type 'str' is not assignable to expected type 'int'
### TITLE ###
ArgsBlockListUseCleanWhenSlotMatches
### DESCRIPTION ###
Args-block list types (`names str[]`) compose with the rest of the
type system - passing one into a `str[]` slot is clean.
### INPUT ###
args:
    names str[]

fn first(xs: str[]) -> str:
    return xs[0]

print(first(names))
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  xs @ 5:12 -> str[]
  print @ 7:1 -> dynamic
  first @ 7:7 -> fn(str[]) -> str
  names @ 7:13 -> str[]

# Symbol types
  first (fn): fn(str[]) -> str
  names (arg): str[]
  xs (param): str[]

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
CmdBlockTypedUseFlagsMismatch
### DESCRIPTION ###
Same enforcement applies to cmd-block decls (SymCmdArg). The cmd's
arg lives in file scope so the callback can read it; here it flows
into a typed function call and fires.
### INPUT ###
command build:
    name str
    calls on_build

fn on_build():
    consume_int(name)

fn consume_int(label: int):
    print(label)
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  consume_int @ 6:5 -> fn(int) -> void
  name @ 6:17 -> str
  print @ 9:5 -> dynamic
  label @ 9:11 -> int

# Symbol types
  consume_int (fn): fn(int) -> void
  label (param): int
  name (cmdarg): str
  on_build (fn): fn() -> void

# Diagnostics
  [hint] RAD30001 @ 6:17 - Argument type 'str' is not assignable to expected type 'int'
### TITLE ###
ArgsBlockOptionalIsNullable
### DESCRIPTION ###
The `?` in `name str?` marks the value as runtime-nullable (no
default, user may omit the flag). The type binds to `str?` so
passing it to a non-nullable `str` slot fires the existing
nullable-suggestion diagnostic; passing it to a `str?` slot is
clean.
### INPUT ###
args:
    name str?

fn need_str(s: str):
    print(s)

fn maybe_str(s: str?):
    print(s)

need_str(name)
maybe_str(name)
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  print @ 5:5 -> dynamic
  s @ 5:11 -> str
  print @ 8:5 -> dynamic
  s @ 8:11 -> str?
  need_str @ 10:1 -> fn(str) -> void
  name @ 10:10 -> str?
  maybe_str @ 11:1 -> fn(str?) -> void
  name @ 11:11 -> str?

# Symbol types
  maybe_str (fn): fn(str?) -> void
  name (arg): str?
  need_str (fn): fn(str) -> void
  s (param): str
  s (param): str?

# Diagnostics
  [hint] RAD30001 @ 10:10 - Argument type 'str?' is not assignable to expected type 'str'
